### Playwright: Mark Tests as Failing with `test.fail`

Source: https://github.com/microsoft/playwright/blob/main/docs/src/test-api/class-test.md

The `test.fail` method marks a test as expected to fail, ensuring Playwright verifies it actually fails. This is useful for acknowledging broken functionality or for conditional test failures based on environment or browser. It can be used as a standalone test declaration or within a test body.

```javascript
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test.fail('not yet ready', async ({ page }) => {
  // ...
});
```

```javascript
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('fail in WebKit', async ({ page, browserName }) => {
  test.fail(browserName === 'webkit', 'This feature is not implemented for Mac yet');
  // ...
});
```

```javascript
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test.fail(({ browserName }) => browserName === 'webkit', 'not implemented yet');

test('fail in WebKit 1', async ({ page }) => {
  // ...
});
test('fail in WebKit 2', async ({ page }) => {
  // ...
});
```

```javascript
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test('less readable', async ({ page }) => {
  test.fail();
  // ...
});
```

