### Annotate Playwright tests within a group

Source: https://github.com/microsoft/playwright/blob/main/docs/src/test-api/class-test.md

This example demonstrates how to add annotations to all tests within a `test.describe` group. Annotations provide additional metadata, such as issue links, for better test context and reporting within test results.

```javascript
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test.describe('two annotated tests', {
  annotation: {
    type: 'issue',
    description: 'https://github.com/microsoft/playwright/issues/23180',
  },
}, () => {
  test('one', async ({ page }) => {
    // ...
  });

  test('two', async ({ page }) => {
    // ...
  });
});
```

--------------------------------

### Apply Multiple Playwright Annotations or Group-Level Annotations

Source: https://github.com/microsoft/playwright/blob/main/docs/src/test-annotations-js.md

This example showcases two ways to apply annotations: either as a single object to an entire test group (`test.describe`) or as an array of objects for multiple annotations on an individual test. Group annotations apply to all tests within that `describe` block, while individual test annotations can capture specific details like performance issues.

```js
import { test, expect } from '@playwright/test';

test.describe('report tests', {
  annotation: { type: 'category', description: 'report' },
}, () => {
  test('test report header', async ({ page }) => {
    // ...
  });

  test('test full report', {
    annotation: [
      { type: 'issue', description: 'https://github.com/microsoft/playwright/issues/23180' },
      { type: 'performance', description: 'very slow test!' },
    ],
  }, async ({ page }) => {
    // ...
  });
});
```

